  ```markdown
  # ARGUMENT: DEFENDANT LIABLE FOR NEGLIGENCE

  ## I. DEFENDANT BREACHED ITS DUTY OF CARE

  ### A. Applicable Legal Standard

  Under California law, a manufacturer owes a duty to design and produce
  products free from defects that could cause foreseeable harm to users.
  (*Barker v. Lull Eng'g Co.*, 20 Cal.3d 413, 430 (1978)). A manufacturer
  breaches this duty when it knows or should know of a defect yet fails to
  remedy it. (*Anderson v. Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corp.*, 53 Cal.3d 987,
  995 (1991)).

  ### B. Application to Facts

  ACME breached its duty in three ways:

  **First, ACME knew of the brake defect.** On February 12, 2024, ACME's
  Engineering Manager Sarah Chen personally inspected the brake assembly
  and identified an improper weld on the caliper mounting bracket. [Depo.
  of Chen, p.47, lines 12-18; Engineering Log, PROD-2024-005678]. Chen
  immediately documented the defect and notified management. [Email, Chen
  to Manufacturing Director, PROD-2024-005702, Feb. 13, 2024]. This evidence
  establishes actual knowledge‚ÄîACME cannot claim ignorance.

  **Second, ACME deliberately chose to continue production despite knowledge.**
  At an executive meeting on February 20, 2024, ACME's CEO and senior
  management discussed the brake defect. [Meeting Minutes, PROD-2024-005801,
  p.3]. Rather than halt production, they decided to "sell current inventory
  as-is with extended warranty" to meet "production deadlines." [*Id.*] This
  conscious decision to prioritize profit over safety constitutes a clear
  breach of duty.

  **Third, ACME failed to warn consumers or remedy the defect.** Despite
  knowing of the defect on February 12, ACME took no remedial action until
  April 1, 2024‚Äîseven weeks later and only after plaintiff's injury. [Investigation
  Report, PROD-2024-011234]. No warning was issued, no recall initiated, no
  retrofit offered. This failure to act constitutes a breach of the ongoing
  duty to warn. (*Anderson*, 53 Cal.3d at 1002).

  ### C. Analogous Precedent

  ACME's conduct mirrors the defendant's in *Grimshaw v. Ford Motor Co.*,
  119 Cal.App.3d 757 (1981), where Ford knew of a fuel tank defect but
  conducted a cost-benefit analysis and chose not to remedy it. The court
  held this constituted a conscious disregard for safety, justifying punitive
  damages. [*Id.* at 819]. Here, as in *Grimshaw*, ACME made a calculated
  business decision to sell defective products despite actual knowledge‚Äî
  textbook breach of duty.

  ### D. Rebuttal to Anticipated Defenses

  **Defense Argument #1:** "ACME met industry standards."

  **Rebuttal:** Industry custom is evidence of reasonable care but not
  dispositive. (*Trimarco v. Klein*, 56 N.Y.2d 98, 105 (1982)). Even if
  others in the industry engage in similar cost-cutting, knowingly selling
  defective brakes violates the duty of care. Moreover, ACME's own engineer
  identified the weld as "improperly" done [Chen Depo., p.47], indicating
  a failure to meet even industry standards.

  **Defense Argument #2:** "The defect affected only a small percentage of units."

  **Rebuttal:** Breach of duty is not excused by limited scope. A manufacturer
  who knowingly sells even one defective product breaches its duty to that
  consumer. (*Soule v. General Motors Corp.*, 8 Cal.4th 548, 560 (1994)).
  The 15,000-unit recall demonstrates the defect's scope was substantial,
  but even if only plaintiff's unit were affected, the breach remains.

  **Defense Argument #3:** "ACME eventually issued a recall."

  **Rebuttal:** A post-injury recall does not cure a pre-injury breach.
  The duty was breached when ACME knew of the defect (Feb. 12) yet continued
  sales. Plaintiff was injured March 15, before any remedial action. The
  subsequent recall (May 15) merely confirms ACME's eventual acknowledgment
  of the defect.

  ## II. ACME'S BREACH CAUSED PLAINTIFF'S INJURIES

  ### A. Applicable Legal Standard

  Causation requires proof that defendant's breach was a substantial factor
  in bringing about the harm. (*Rutherford v. Owens-Illinois, Inc.*, 16
  Cal.4th 953, 968-69 (1997)). Plaintiff need not eliminate all other
  possible causes, only show defendant's conduct was a substantial contributing
  factor. (*Mitchell v. Gonzales*, 54 Cal.3d 1041, 1052 (1991)).

  ### B. Application to Facts

  The causal chain is direct and unbroken:

  1. **Defect existed in plaintiff's vehicle.** Independent mechanic inspection
     confirmed "brake caliper mounting bracket weld failure" in plaintiff's
     vehicle immediately after the incident. [Inspection Report, PROD-2024-010456,
     Mar. 16, 2024]. This defect type matches exactly Chen's February 12
     finding. [Chen Depo., p.47].

  2. **Defect caused brake failure.** Plaintiff's vehicle exhibited complete
     brake failure while driving, resulting in inability to stop. [Depo. of
     Plaintiff, p.23, lines 5-10]. Mechanic report confirms weld failure
     caused caliper detachment, eliminating brake function. [Inspection Report].

  3. **Brake failure caused collision and injuries.** Unable to stop, plaintiff's
     vehicle collided with guardrail at 45 mph. [Police Report, EXH-15]. Collision
     caused broken arm, concussion, and vehicle total loss. [Medical Records,
     PROD-2024-010567; Property Damage Assessment, PROD-2024-010589].

  This straightforward chain‚Äîdefect ‚Üí brake failure ‚Üí collision ‚Üí injury‚Äî
  satisfies the substantial factor test.

  ### C. Rebuttal to Anticipated Defenses

  **Defense Argument #4:** "Plaintiff's driving caused the accident, not the defect."

  **Rebuttal:** Plaintiff was driving lawfully at posted speed limit in daylight
  on dry pavement. [Police Report]. No evidence of reckless driving, impairment,
  or distraction. The sudden, total brake failure‚Äînot any driving behavior‚Äî
  caused the collision. Even assuming plaintiff could have driven more
  defensively, the defect remains a substantial factor. (*Weirum v. RKO General,
  Inc.*, 15 Cal.3d 40, 49 (1975)) (conduct need not be sole cause).

  **Defense Argument #5:** "Other factors could have caused brake failure."

  **Rebuttal:** Speculation about alternative causes does not defeat causation.
  (*Daubert v. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc.*, 43 F.3d 1311, 1320 (9th
  Cir. 1995)). Here, plaintiff's expert will testify the weld defect was
  the cause to a reasonable degree of engineering certainty. [Expert Report,
  Dr. Engineering, forthcoming]. Moreover, ACME's own investigation confirmed
  the defect in plaintiff's batch. [Investigation Report, PROD-2024-011234].

  ## III. CONCLUSION

  ACME knew of a deadly defect, chose profit over safety, and sold defective
  brakes that failed and injured plaintiff. This is precisely the conduct
